< text>
I went with family for the first time ever around the holidays, and everyone loved their dish, including the kids (they have kids menu). It's a nice place, it felt and looked clean, with beautiful decor, enough outdoor seating. The service was great and so was the food. After lunch we had some good coffee and they served it in the cutest mugs. I will be definitely coming back and try more dishes!</text>

< text>
Best Mexican food in Modesto. The only reason I didn't give them 5 stars  is because  almost every time I go there and get an order to go., When I get home  something is missing. I usually order a lot of food to take out  and its  pretty hard to take everything out of the bag and check it.  I guess ill have to start doing that tho. Got home last week and my refried beans wasn't in the bag.  tonight   i asked for extra salsa   got home   No extra salsa  But they gave me extra jalapenos.  Nice people tho. Very friendly service. They just seem to keep forgetting what I ordered.<//text>

<gmap_id>0x80dc754f6c9acc13:0x1961fef653696cdb<//gmap_id><resp>None</resp>< Text>
Probably deserves 3.5 stars.  Old school sports bar.  We had hot dogs, fries and tater tots, and all were very good. Staff was friendly and attentive - although they forgot to put in our order so it took close to an hour. But they were very apologetic and they gave us complimentary tots.  Between the music and TVs, very loud - it is, after all, a sports bar. They have a couple of pool tables and arcade games.  Not sure it's ideal for watching a game you're really into - more for casual viewing.  I was surprised at how limited the beer selection was though.  Overall, pretty decent place, nice staff, good enough food.< /Text>

<text>The 55 Yard line is a Chargers bar, but as a born & bred local that also means were not that passionate about them. We welcome everyone, even that one Raiders fan. You will always see Denver fans. As a city of transplants we understand that and respect is returned.

It can get packed, SRO, but with the chargers being especially disappointing it‚Äôs less so. Having a BWW right next door doesn‚Äôt help business either, so this really does become a locals only hang out.

They offer more local and craft beers than more widely popular restaurant/bars like The Draft and the food is solid offering Artichoke Dip, cheese filled pretzels. Solid fries and onion rings. Prices on beers (craft are 6-7) while the domestics are a buck or two cheaper. They offer most beers in a pint or 23 oz. Burgers are good, better than most places.

Service is good at the bar and seated because they have staffing running through all areas pretty steady you usually don‚Äôt have to flag anyone down. I steer clear of cocktails involving more than 3 ingredients.  Stick to beer. Glassware is clean and surprisingly new, generally places that push a lot of beer tend to not update their glassware as often as they should. Jim the owner is a good dude, always here working.

Outdoor patio is really only where smokers hang out and some TV‚Äôs have a few second delay, you can tell the upgrades and renovations were done in stages as many of the TV‚Äôs don‚Äôt match. Pool outsideThis place is dead outside of football and basketball season. Summertime Sadness.</text>< Rate>

< Review>
Wandered through this park a few days ago and it was quite cute and pleasant. It has a decent trail and a quaint pond in the middle of it. The park connects to many parts of the neighborhood, and seems like the perfect way to sneak in an after work bike ride. It's well lit and has a good deal of wild life. It has some good peace of mind to it and is in the middle of the suburbs. From an outsider's perspective it's a very decent neighborhood park.<//Review>

<Review>I love this park.  Last summer I broke my foot and had a knee walker to roll around on the greenbelt.  I would walk 2-4  miles everyday.  I realized how bad the greenbelts in Davis are for people that need assistance and/or use wheeled devices. Bicycles as well. The asphalt has big cracks, and bumps made by tree roots.  I almost fell down several times during my walks with wheels.  I think it is tricky using a wheeled device if you don't pay close attention to the terrain.  A level stretch of cement is located North of Sandpiper, Covell Drainage Channel that runs about 3 blocks. Can be accessed on Sandpiper Drive on the East end at the curve.  It would be great for all if our greenbelt paths could be made with cement.</Review>< user>

< review>
For the record, I've been eating at various Round Table Pizza restaurants since I was a young. It's my favorite local area pizza chain.
And this particular shop is one that I used to frequent back in the nineties when I had friends that worked there. So I have a pretty good idea of what to expect.
That being said, I really only have one complaint...
If you can't cook the pizza properly (make sure the dough is fully cooked) then maybe Monday Appreciation day should no longer exist.
I get that it's a promotion that fills the joint and that customers, like my wife, really appreciate because of the savings; but I've started to ignore the savings and save my stomach.
Last night was the first time in a while that we've been to this restaurant.
(Del's pizza up the street makes a great Garlic pizza and it's fully cooked, but expensive).
I won't be back again on a Monday as the problem still exists.
The Pizzas are fine on other days. But Mondays are a no go.< /review>

First I will start with a positive. Pizza is great and up to par with where it should be. My reasoning for this review is to hopefully make one small change that makes a difference to people's opinion of a restaurant. Me pregunto que es de la vida de aquellas personas llaman tratando de encontrar una repuesta que en ese momento es determinante para el rumbo de sus vidas.
Pero no pudo contactar al pastor por falta de seres humanos que contestaran a su llamada.
Dios quiera que esto no pase en todas las iglesias.</review>

We were looking for a no-chain coffee shop for breakfast. We found Dos Hermanos. It exceeded our expectations. My breakfast burrito was eggxcelent and they were accommodating to my daughter's vegan diet. She ordered the burrito in a bowl. Our order took about 20 minutes but everything was fresh and yummy. The wait was totally worth it. Also, there's a sign telling you about the wait which I think is really useful. The person at the register was helpful and cordial.< /Review>

<Response>None</Response><Text>In the continuing effort to locate, taste and report on the breakfast burritos of the county, I bring Dos Hermanos Breakfast burritos. What fun, A nice drive to San Miguel to test another burrito. The place is busy, I mean busy, 20 minutes for a burrito. There are locals, to go orders, soldiers from Camp Roberts, and us! Popular, or the best place in town.. Well that is for each individual to decide. I had the chili verde breakfast burrito and my son had the bacon burrito. We were both very pleased with the content, size, preparation and flavors. I will be returning and bringing friends, relatives and others to this place to test the menu further. The staff are working their tails off as they serve both the in house and to go orders and are oh so polite and pleasant as they work. I will be back. Thank you Dos Hermanos! And I love the murals and the colorful decor, both inside and out! If you are on the freeway, pull off and enjoy a burrito, or call in an order and enjoy it in the park just up the street, either way it is a good stop.<//Text><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< Time>

I have been taking my cats to Monrovia Animal Medical Center for many years.  "Dr. G" and the staff are great.  Dr. G was very comforting when I had to put my beloved Patches to sleep.  I was not expecting the bad news, and, although I was very upset, she gently persuaded me to do what needed to be done. <Resp>{'time': 1542039741495, 'text': 'Hello Paul,  We appreciate you taking your time to provide a positive rating! We are excited that you are enjoying your experience at Park 12. Thank you, and have a fantastic day!'}<//Resp><review>Original post written November 2018

An awesome place to call home!

We've been here about 2 months, and so far I have found nothing negative about this place. The views of Petco Park, Point Loma and the Pacific Ocean from our higher floor are absolutely stunning.

The appliances are brand new and top-notch, and the geek in me just loves the fact that I was able to choose which fiber internet provider I wanted - AT&T or Cox. Both offer full gig speeds up and down here at the building. Throw in the eight CAT6 network drops that are located throughout the apartment and you have a home network that is pretty much the envy of any tech person - which is who they are probably targeting.

The central A/C works great. The floor to ceiling windows in the living room and bedroom are very nice. There‚Äôs nothing quite like waking up and looking at Petco Park or watching a Navy ship return to port.

Parking is provided via the gated underground garage.  First space is free, unlike other downtown apartments that charge over $100 per month for your first parking spot. Parking spaces are wide, which is probably a good thing, as there are a lot of high end cars in the garage.  The proximity of the Gaslamp Quarter is just icing on the cake.

I almost forgot to mention the staff.  They are wonderful.

What's not to love :)

UPDATE - 11 May

I still give this place 5 stars. All of the amenities are now up and running. No issues with the homeless like some other reviewers have stated. Area around Park 12 is MUCH better than the rest of East Village - It‚Äôs all part of living downtown.

I will definitely renew my lease :)<//review>< name>

<text>I am a new resident to Park 12 and I was very hesitant with becoming a renter again after being a homeowner for over 12 years.  But, I was seeking a change in scenery and very much so wanted to experience living in Downtown San Diego again with my son.  I am a native San Diegan and I had toured several apartment buildings over several weeks and finally came across Park 12.  Being that we are currently in the midst of a pandemic my expectations were high as it relates to safety and customer service. <Date>1567718229825< /Date><rating>1< /rating><review>I hope this review will help anyone who is thinking of renting here. I was an employee of Park 12 who has been here since the property opened and worked here until a few weeks ago. I was not fired and I am not a disgruntled employee. I am giving an honest unbiased review so I hope you take this for what it's worth.
The property itself is beautiful and I loved the residents here so much.  Unfortunately, over the last few months, the management team that is in place here has run Park 12 into the ground. They have absolutely no idea what they are doing and it is definitely starting to show. The leasing agents who are there do the best they can with minimal support from management. When the City building opened, management moved over there in an effort to completely wall themselves off from residents and staff. Any emails to management from staff members or residents go unanswered and if they do decide to respond they will only address what they feel like. Residents and staff are rarely told the truth (examples: parking: there is NO guest parking and information on amenities changes all the time).
I've been in this industry for almost 30 years and I've never seen a management team behave is such an unprofessional way. The biggest problem at Park 12 is the Leasing Manager . Rude and unprofessional and lacking any customer service skills, you can see why there are numerous negative reviews just about her on this very website. I'm shocked at how paying residents and their guests are treated and it's just disgraceful.
Management will lie to your face just to avoid telling you the truth. The amenities are nice but are not controlled or kept impeccably clean.The game room is a disaster with things always broken, and the pet park is a smelly disgusting mess.
Do yourself a favor and look at another property if you want to reside in the East Village. There are so many other options out there where you will be appreciated and respected. For the rents they are charging, it's not worth it, so I would suggest you look elsewhere. The residents and staff here at Park 12 DESERVE a better management team then what is in place here right now. It's a shame, because the property is nice, but when you have such an insufferable and incompetent management team, it makes living here as a resident a huge challenge. <Review>Future Tenants BEWARE. There is a 3 million dollar renovation currently underway at Park 12. The building is only 2 years old and already a water main pipe burst on the 30th floor. All elevators were closed for 2 days and continue to have issues since. This forced me to climb up and down over 25 flights of stairs multiple times a day. What about the residents with physical disabilities? My parents were one of those people being trapped in my own apartment forced to spend the night without medication.

It has been over 2 weeks now and you have constant construction going on in the hallways. There is water damage on practically every floor. Moving crews and contractors pack the rarely available elevators with their equipment. You have to wait a life time just to be packed in like sardines.

I don't blame onsite management but at the corporate level they are dropping the ball. No type of compensation is being offered. I have other tenants passing out law firm business cards for people that want someone to help them break their lease.

For how much I pay to live here it's not worth this headache. I would expect this from Pinnacle but not Park 12. That's saying something.

Go to Shift or Alexan.< /Review>< Pictures>

And the leasing agent was a gentleman that was very uninformative and a little rude. Also, I know its not his fault however I find it odd I can't receive any pricing information unless I go into the office. I've worked in property management and have never heard of anything like that. I just feel like a building such as this should have better service and not have someone on the phone that sounds miserable being there.</text>

<time>1619828114012</time>< Review>
PHASE 3 : The Villas at CMV
Casa Mira View labels itself "LUXURY apartments" while the amenities are unique and plentiful. Daily life at CVM the Villas is far from luxury.

THE GOOD:
Maintenance is prompt and polite. We have had appliance issues in our brand new unit, and maintenance has been quick, effective, and professional. Cleaning crew works hard in attempt to maintain community, they are nice people. Leasing office staff is friendly. Location is convenient to the freeway and shopping.

THE BAD:
Parking: There are not enough spaces for the number of units in community. While you will receive your single or double assigned spaces according to the number of bedrooms in unit, there are only 20 overflow spaces (in a complex of 200 units) if you have a second vehicle in a 1 bedroom unit, you will not have anywhere to park your vehicle. There are 21 "guests" spaces (which are used by residence, not guests, that have not registered their vehicles). This means that 10% of the Villas are able to have a single guest at any given time, which you can imagine is a challenge during holidays. After 4pm there is zero parking outside of assigned space, and half of the 200 units are not occupied so you can anticipate it will only get worse. The leasing office will recommend parking in the overflow of the other phases or parking on the street which is 2 city blocks away from your unit. We often must carry groceries 15 minutes from phase 2 garage to our apartment (LUXURY).

Unit Noise: I have never lived in an apartment with so little noise insulation between units. We literally hear every step, every cabinet close, movie watched and child scream from our neighbor. The "Luxury vinyl plank flooring"  in all units seems nice until you realize that without extra sound insulating material it is a nightmare (OMG SO LUXURY).

Freeway: Being next to a freeway and a "park-and-ride" lot, you will hear every siren, car meet, and general freeway noise at every moment. This property has not installed a sound wall, but a iron fence which does nothing to provide privacy or noise control to the community. The view of the "park-and -ride" lot provides residents an opportunity to see abandoned furniture and trash through their living room window (SMELL THAT LUXURY).

Animal waste: Pet feces and urine is throughout the community. Although there are pet stations in the Villas, there is urine and feces on the floor, on the pillars every day. The cleaning crew is fantastic and cleans it daily, but without enforcement by property, the sight and smell of animal waste is constant (VERY LUXURY woof woof).

Package theft: There are package lockers in the mail room which seems like a great amenity, but because the lockers are shared by all 3 phases they are often full. This results in packages being left in piles on the floor of the mail room or at your front, where in my experience will likely be stolen. Ive had 4 packages stolen, one I caught in the act, while living at the Villas (NOW THATS LUXURY).

The solution to each of these negatives by management is to use curtesy patrol. But it is not the tenants responsibility to repeatedly report ongoing issues that are known and unaddressed by property management. Additionally reporting to curtesy patrol is a pacifier that finds no resolve.</Review>

I have been living here just shy of two months and wanted to wait before giving this review. Similar to other tenants, the noise level at this property is the worst of the other properties I had lived in.

We live here with the upstairs neighbors and they are constantly walking loudly and stomping during the community's quiet hours. I had made numerous complaints by calling security, submitting tickets to their property management website, and even relaying this over to the managers on site.

Even though the managers were nice and seeming apologetic, but they seem to give me the same run-around like with other tenants (keep calling security for them to document the noise and send them video recordings and we will remind the neighbor about noise levels). <review>Our overall experience here was okay. The surrounding area is great (especially for families), the office staff were alright, and the amenities were really nice. We had no issues with move in/move out processes.

We were told to record them, but later told that the only recordings that mattered were the ones made by the courtesy patrol from the hallway. CMV is like living at a resort!  My experience has been nothing less than exceptional. I made contact with the leasing office through the website, and was called as soon as they opened in the morning. < text>
We moved in late December and we love it here. Like every apartment, they have their ups and downs, but honestly there are much more ups here than what I have experienced with the numerous apartments we've lived in previously. First off, you get some outdoor space as the balconies are HUGE which is a big plus for me. Maintenance is great, very professional. The staff is pretty good, I've even met with the director, Wendy, and she is AWESOME and is very down to earth and helpful. The size of our apartment is HUGE compared to what we were able to find in the area for our price point, although the rent seems high, they are actually very reasonable considering the square footage you get. Yes the speed bumps are annoying as all get out, but people DO speed in the parking garage like they are on the freakin' freeway! The only other real con is my neighbors upstairs are likely running a gym or something because they are the loudest neighbors I've ever had in my life, but that's not the apartment's fault. We plan on living here until we are ready to buy a place and we'll be sure to miss living here with all of its amazing amenities (although the sooner we can get some community grills on the property, the better ;-)). Also, I did want to add that the place is seriously energy efficient; the utilities are REALLY low. I lived in a place half the size of this place and the electricity bill was higher there than what I pay here, and I am not afraid to use the A/C; the water is about the same as the place I lived in previously that was half the size, still great.<//text>

Turns out they had lost the email. My own copy of the email, which I forwarded to them, showed very clearly I had sent them the file the day that they had asked. Then, months later, they claim the paperwork STILL wasn't complete. Why? Because I had listed my previous address from A MONTH BEFORE THE LEASE as my address when I had turned in the paperwork prior to move in. They wanted the address I would move into once I started the lease. Why they didn't tell me that 8 months prior when I initially turned in the paperwork is beyond me.

There was also the incident where I was being cyberstalked, harassed, and threatened to the point where I no longer felt safe living at the apartment. I went to the leasing office and explained the situation. Despite the threat to my safety, they said there was no way they could release me from the lease, even if I found a replacement. To make matters worse, the leasing office shared this private information with one of my roommates via email when she mistakenly sent a follow-up email to her instead of me.

I wasn't going to continue living in a place where I felt my safety was in jeopardy, so my roommates agreed to handle rent and I moved out. I told the leasing office I was no longer living there and asked for them to note it in the file and also to stop contacting me regarding the apartment, given I was no longer living there. Since I was the one who mainly interacted with the leasing office when initially getting the apartment for my group, the leasing office often used me as the primary contact and wanted me to pass information along to my roommates. The leasing office said they still had to contact me, since I was on the lease, but that they would note to contact me last.

That didn't happen. Got an email addressed solely to me from the leasing office asking if I still wanted additional parking spaces for the apartment. Why would I care about additional parking spaces for an apartment I don't even live at?

I don't normally write reviews on Google, but the complete disorganization and incompetency of the leasing office these past 8 months drove me to this point. It's not that hard to actually check paperwork or keep track of it. It's not that hard to contact the correct individual on the lease in regards to their personal situations. It's not that hard to read the apartment file and see that I'm no longer the primary contact on the lease. I'm so done with this place and can't wait for my lease to be over so I will never have to deal with this organization again.

That being said, the maintenance staff is prompt and nice. Apartments themselves are nice and spacious. Good insulation in terms of heat and sound. Again, the amenities are great. However, parking. Parking is a b. You only get one car per bedroom you rent. So, if you're sharing a 1 bedroom with someone, only one of you get a parking spot. If you're sharing a 2 bedroom, you only get two parking spots. Parking without an assigned spot is impossible. Guest spots are constantly filled by guests or residents without enough parking spaces. So if you want to host someone at your new swanky apartment, maybe bring them to the hot tub...don't bother. They'll drive to you only to not be able to find a guest spot on the garage. Street parking isn't easy either and it can be a long walk.

If you're willing to pay their pricetag, do yourself a favor and get a nicer place somewhere nearby.</Review>< name>

<user>101007252155615076245</user><username>Boris Fratkin</username><date>1502815212964<//date><rate>5<//rate><review>I feel bad for the people who had a bad experience with Casa Mira View.

I personally had experienced nothing but good and kindness from the leasing office so far. Everyone who I worked with for my issues and concerns helped me quite a bit in a very responsive way! The ladies to great you at the front desk at the leasing office are very friendly and nice. Very warm. I have absolutely no complaints, and certainly no shallow complaints such as the bumps in the parking lot structure going to the fifth floor type a thing...

You don't like the bumps get an apartment on the first floor.. It is your decision, nobody made you sign it. When signing a lease, make sure to do your own walk-around and think-about on all possible future issues you might have with the new place BEFORE signing.

I am coming from LA. And reading these comments here about Casa Mira View make me laugh. If you are coming from LA and live in a similar complex over there, you would have so much more complaints- TRUST ME. Someone here said "regulations." Every new condo apartments complex of such size anywhere else outside of SD will have regulations, and issues here and there, especially when it goes under construction as they lease. It's just the way it is. People expect to be handed everything on a silver plate because they pay the rent therefore they're obligated. For the most part, they are right.. but majority of the time when it pertains to these shallow comments here - they are certainly not.

I have been asked by maintenance guy to comment on his work  so I give a guy 5 stars because he deserves it. I dont think there is anything wrong with asking that as long as you do your job right. His name is Jorge Ramirez, by the way. He tried his best to take care of whatever maintenance items we had (we had a long list after moving into apartment that someone was living in before us for a year or so.  Good job Jorge! I think all the guys in maintenance team are really taking care of requests properly (had been living in this community for almost 4 years now and never had any problems with them in terms of timeliness, accommodating your schedule and quality of work and other things of that sort).
Giving three stars to the community as a whole due to them seem unable to take care of following things:
--smoke-free status - they are unable to enforce it as smoking folks seem to find ways to smoke in the parking area, in their apartments (i suppose by tampering with smoke detectors), on balconies and patios hiding behind poles etc., so actually fumes make their way into non-smoker's homes and common areas;
--pet-free section (phase II) - is not a pet-free at all as folks are finding ways to have pets (mostly dogs) on the pretexts of those being companion (often times multiple) dogs. Not sure why they don't put those tenants into pet-friendly quarters at time of signing lease. I dont think anyone of them is paying high pet-rent either. I would like to have a little kitty, but it is $50 per month plus deposit, yeah, guess dont have that much of love left in me...;
--breaking the lease - they changed terms and now there is no flat-rate penalty provision left in there, so depending on the market you can get stuck paying high rent for the remainder of term if no one wants the unit, be cautious.
-- water/trash payment organization is not lenient for latency and charging $5 late fee, although they do not provide ebill service that can be paid in automated way and amount is changing based on usage so you have to be sure you follow up on each bill manually  for payment clearing before due date.

Probably i missed something else important here, will add if remember later.

Thank you for reading...<//review>

Looks good, but it's a ghetto!
The rent prices are close to unrealistic, though most people shrug it off to the many amenities they offer for curb appeal which are RARELY in working order, and when they are they're a shitshow of unsupervised children jumping, splashing, and eating in the hottub...etc.  For what they charge for rentals they fail to mention that half the property is low-income housing, so you'll be paying to neighbour with that.
The "smoke-free facility" is a joke - the place is littered with cigarette butts and I don't go a day without seeing and/or smelling someone smoking, mainly the staff/security, which explains why they're never at their stations -
Parking is an additional charge, but it's pointless because our parking stall is taken ALL THE TIME and Casa Mira staff/security do NOTHING about it.  They won't even allow you to have the illegally parked car towed from your PAID stall. They suggest you street park until your stall is open.
This is the only rental I've ever been in that passes their renter responsibilities off on the tenants, ie fresh paint and carpet cleaning between tenants.  This is without proof of wear and tear, this is standard contract, on top of your mandatory monthly fee for renters insurance.
And though they claim they provide maintenance, in 6 months and five service calls (for the same two issues) we've NEVER seen it.
We're on our way out, and from what we've read, we don't expect to see our deposit (despite leaving the apt in immaculate condition) we're just praying they don't try to scam us out of a couple hundred dollars worth of charges like they have other renters.< /Text>

<date>1556696100984<//date>< Review>
I love this market. The meats are always fresh and the staff is usually knowledgeable and polite. I have purchased some of their cooked foods as well which are really great. The only one thing I'm not a fan of is there fish ceviche, I find that the fish is cut in such huge chunks that the lemon and other flavors do not penetrate as well as might be expected the end result is a little too raw and fishy for my taste. Of course that is just my preference. The shrimp and octopus ceviche however is delicious. As are their tripitas and guacamole.< /Review>
